[I🔥 Level 1 – Timer as a Pure Time Base (Update Event Mastery)
Task 1: 1ms Heartbeat Using General Timer (NOT SysTick)

Do not use SysTick. Disable HAL time base if needed.

Configure a general-purpose timer (like TIM2 or TIM3) to generate an update interrupt every 1 ms.

Inside the ISR:

Increment a volatile uint32_t ms_counter.

In main():

Every 1000 ms, toggle an LED.

Every 5000 ms, print something via UART (but NOT inside ISR).

What this forces you to understand:

Prescaler calculation

ARR calculation

Update interrupt enable

Clearing UIF flag

Why volatile matters

Keeping ISR short

Software time tracking

If your LED drifts → your math is wrong.

🔥 Level 2 – PWM Deep Understanding
Task 2: LED Brightness Ramp (ARR vs CCR Separation)

Use PWM mode on a timer channel connected to an LED.

Keep:

ARR fixed (so frequency constant, e.g., 1 kHz).

Gradually change CCR from 0 → ARR → 0.

Create a smooth breathing LED effect.

Rules:

Change CCR inside main loop.

Do NOT stop/restart the timer.

Do NOT reinitialize the timer.

This forces:

Understanding that ARR controls frequency.

CCR controls duty.

PWM is hardware-driven.

Timer runs independently of CPU.

If LED flickers → frequency too low.
If brightness jumps → you misunderstand duty cycle scaling.

🔥 Level 3 – Multi-Channel PWM Synchronization
Task 3: 3 LEDs, 1 Timer, Different Duty Cycles

Use one timer.
Enable 3 channels.
Use same ARR.

Set:

CH1 = 25%

CH2 = 50%

CH3 = 75%

Observe:

All LEDs share same frequency.

Only duty differs.

Then change ARR dynamically.
Watch what happens to brightness and frequency.

This cements:

Single counter, multiple CCR registers.

Frequency is shared across channels.

🔥 Level 4 – Input Capture Frequency Measurement
Task 4: Measure Your Own PWM

Connect:
PWM output pin → jumper wire → input capture pin.

Use one timer for PWM.
Use another timer in input capture mode.

Measure frequency of your own PWM signal.

Steps:

Capture two rising edges.

Compute difference.

Convert to Hz.

Then:

Change PWM frequency.

Verify measured frequency changes accordingly.

This forces:

Edge selection

Reading CCR values

Period calculation

Clock understanding

If measurement unstable → noise or overflow not handled.

🔥 Level 5 – Pulse Width Measurement
Task 5: Duty Cycle Analyzer

Using same loopback setup.

Capture:

Rising edge timestamp

Falling edge timestamp

Compute:

High time

Period

Duty cycle %

Display via UART.

Now change CCR of PWM and verify measured duty matches expected.

If mismatch → overflow handling wrong or edge config wrong.

🔥 Level 6 – Overflow Handling Stress Test
Task 6: Slow Signal, Small Timer

Configure:

Timer at high speed

ARR small (force frequent overflow)

Measure a slow PWM signal so overflow occurs between edges.

Implement overflow compensation logic.

If your measured frequency suddenly becomes negative or garbage → overflow math is wrong.

This one separates theory readers from embedded engineers.

🔥 Level 7 – SysTick vs General Timer Conflict
Task 7: Break HAL_Delay On Purpose

Change SysTick frequency manually.

Observe HAL_Delay behaving incorrectly.

Then move HAL time base to TIM6.

Verify HAL_Delay works again.

This teaches:

SysTick is HAL backbone.

Time base override concept.

Why RTOS conflicts happen.

🔥 Level 8 – ISR Discipline Challenge
Task 8: Intentionally Break System

Inside timer ISR:

Add printf.

Add HAL_Delay(10).

Watch system freeze or behave strangely.

Then remove them.
Observe stability return.

You will never again misuse ISR.

🔥 Level 9 – Real-World Signal Measurement
Task 9: Measure External Signal

Use:

Function generator OR

Another microcontroller OR

Servo control signal OR

IR sensor output

Measure real signal frequency and duty.

Now you’re no longer testing your own generated signal.
You’re measuring unpredictable real-world edges.

This exposes noise, filtering, and edge detection realities.

🔥 Level 10 – Timer-Based Cooperative Scheduler

Final boss.

Using only:

One general timer update interrupt at 1 ms

Build:

Task A runs every 10 ms

Task B runs every 100 ms

Task C runs every 1000 ms

No RTOS.
No blocking delays.

Pure software scheduling using timer tick.

If you can do this cleanly,
you fully understand update events, ISR rules, and time base architecture.
